name: Oksana
bio: [('Beginning', 'She took up gymnastics at age seven. (Asiad Daily, 26 Sep 2014)'), ('Debut', '1987 for Soviet Union (sportcentric.com, 06 Oct 2013)'), ('Coach', 'Svetlana Boguinskaia [personal], BLR (gazeta.uz, 07 Feb 2018)'), ('Training', 'She trains for 15 to 20 hours a week. (fig-gymnastics.com, 01 Jun 2017)'), ('Ambition', 'To compete at the 2020 Olympic Games in Tokyo. (fig-gymnastics.com, 01 Jun 2017)'), ('Awards', 'She was inducted into the International Gymnastics Hall of Fame in May 2017. (intlgymnast.com, 21 May 2017)She holds the title of Honoured Master of Sport in Uzbekistan. (anons.uz, 03 Dec 2013)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralOLYMPIC FIRSTShe became the first gymnast to compete at seven Olympic Games when she competed at the 2016 Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro. In 2017 she also announced that she would try to qualify for her eighth Olympic Games, in 2020 in Tokyo. "I am taking it step by step to see how far physically my body will take me. Of course I want to do more, otherwise I would not be training." (fig-gymnastics.com, 01 Jun 2017; intlgymnast.com, 21 May 2017; SportsDeskOnline, 29 Jul 2018)CAREERBorn in Bukhara, Uzbekistan, she made her international debut for the Soviet Union. Following the dissolution of the Soviet Union, she represented the Commonwealth of Independent States [CIS] at the 1992 Olympic Games in Barcelona and later began competing for Uzbekistan. In 2002 her son Alisher was diagnosed with leukaemia, so her family moved to Germany where he could receive treatment. She obtained German citizenship in 2006, winning a silver medal for her adopted nation at the 2008 Olympic Games in Beijing. She returned to compete for Uzbekistan in 2013, having been given special dispensation by the executive committee of the International Gymnastics Federation [FIG]. (uznews.net, 06 Mar 2013; heraldscotland.com, 16 Oct 2015)FROM TEAMMATE TO COACHShe and her coach, Svetlana Boguinskaya, were members of the gold medal-winning Unified team at the 1992 Olympic Games in Barcelona, Spain. (sports-reference.com, 28 Jul 1992)ATHLETE REPRESENTATIVEIn October 2017 she was elected the women\'s artistic gymnastics representative for the International Gymnastics Federation [FIG] Athletes Commission. (gymnovosti.com, 06 Oct 2017) '), ('Relatives', 'Her husband Bakhodir Kurbanov represented Uzbekistan in wrestling at the 2000 Olympic Games in Sydney. (sports-reference.com, 12 Aug 2012)'), ('Injuries', 'She was suffering with a foot and ankle injury at the 2014 Asian Games in Incheon, Republic of Korea, so decided to not compete in the all-around and instead compete on vault. (insidethgames.biz, 24 Sep 2014; ndtv.com, 25 Sep 2014)She had an operation on her shoulder in 2008 and required back surgery in January 2009. (gymmedia.de, 17 Jan 2009)She tore her Achilles tendon at the 2008 Swiss Cup in Zurich, Switzerland. (intlgymnast.com, 02 Nov 2008)She sustained a leg injury ahead of the 2004 Olympic Games in Athens, which meant she was only able to compete on vault. (Gymnastica, 27 Oct 2005)'), ('Education', 'Uzbekistan State Institute of Physical Culture, Uzbekistan'), ('Languages', 'English, Russian'), ('Highlights', 'RankEventYearLocationResultAsian name: DENIS
bio: [('Beginning', 'He began the sport at age four in Tashkent, Uzbekistan. (Athlete, 20 Aug 2018)'), ('Reason', 'His mother Klaudiya got him involved in tennis. (Athlete, 20 Aug 2018)'), ('Debut', 'Turned professional in 2004'), ('Coach', 'Klaudiya Istomina [mother], RUS, from 1991 (Athlete, 20 Aug 2018)'), ('Memorable', "Winning the ATP [Association of Tennis Professionals] 250 tournaments in Nottingham, England, and Chengdu, People's Republic of China, and reaching the finals of the ATP 250 tournaments in New Haven, CT, United States of America, and Kitzbuhel, Austria. (Athlete, 20 Aug 2018)"), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralNATIONAL FIRSTSHe became first Uzbekistan player to reach the third round at a Grand Slam, achieving the feat at the US Open in 2009. In August 2010 he made his first ATP World Tour final in New Haven, CT, United States of America. Although he lost, he rose to no.39 in the world rankings, becoming the first Uzbekistan player to rank among the top 50. In 2012 at Wimbledon, he reached the fourth round of a Grand Slam tournament for the first time in his career, and repeated the achievement at the US Open in 2013 and the Australian Open in 2017. (sports.ru, 21 Jan 2017; atpworldtour.com, 20 Sep 2010; uzdaily.uz, 30 Aug 2010) '), ('Hero', 'US tennis player Pete Sampras, Russian tennis player Marat Safin. (uz24.uz, 07 Jan 2014)'), ('Influence', 'His mother. (Athlete, 20 Aug 2018)'), ('Nickname', 'Deni (atpworldtour.com, 27 Jun 2016)'), ('Injuries', 'He suffered a knee injury in early 2011. (uzdaily.uz, 21 Sep 2011)In 2001 he suffered a broken leg, hip and wrist in a car accident while he was travelling to play a tournament in Tashkent, Uzbekistan. He spent the following three months in hospital and did not pick up a tennis racket for two years, resuming training in April 2003. As a result of his injuries, he has a 30cm scar at the top of his right leg. (atpworldtour.com, 16 Jul 2012)'), ('Education', 'Coaching - Uzbek State Institute of Physical Education, Tashkent, UZB'), ('Languages', 'Russian, English'), ('Hobbies', 'Football, playing billiards, watching movies. bio: [('Beginning', 'She took up the sport at age eight in Tashkent, Uzbekistan. Certainly, I didn\'t know the name of the sport then but I realised that I liked it madly." name: OLGA
bio: [('Beginning', 'She took up the sport in 1990 in St. Petersburg, Russian Federation. (Athlete, 23 Apr 2016)'), ('Debut', 'Turned professional in 2001'), ('Ambition', 'To compete at the 2016 Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro. (Athlete, 23 Apr 2016)'), ('Awards', 'In recognition of her achievements at the 2012 Olympic Games in London, she received the Order for Merits to the Fatherland [second grade] from the president of the Russian Federation. (kremlin.ru, 13 Aug 2012)She holds the title of Honoured Master of Sport in the Russian Federation. (Athlete, 23 Apr 2016)'), ('Additional Information', 'Type of riderTime-trialist (SportsDeskOnline, 20 Jul 2016)GeneralREPRESENTING UZBEKISTANIn August 2018 she announced her intention to switch allegiances from the Russian Federation to Uzbekistan. She had hoped to compete for Uzbekistan at the 2018 Asian Games in Indonesia, but was deemed ineligible after official communication from the Russian Olympic Committee and Russian Cycling Federation to approve and confirm her release to Uzbekistan were not provided. She filed an application to the Ad-Hoc Division of the Court of Arbitration for Sport [CAS] on-site in Indonesia the day before the women\'s 20km individual time trial at the Games, but it was dismissed and she was unable to take part in the Games. She was motivated to switch allegiances out of concerns she might be ruled ineligible to compete at the 2020 Olympic Games due to a previous doping violation. "You see what has been happening in Russian sport over the last two Olympic cycles. It all started in Rio, then the situation only deteriorated in Pyeongchang. I have a feeling that in Tokyo everything will be even worse. I\'m 99% confident that my participation in the 2020 Olympics will be impossible under the Russian flag." (insidethegames.biz, 23 Aug 2018; olympics.nbcsports.com, 08 Aug 2018)RIO REPRIEVEShe was one of several Russian athletes who were initially denied the opportunity to compete at the 2016 Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro due to previous doping violations. However, just days before the start of the Games, the Court of Arbitration for Sport [CAS] ruled that those athletes should not be prevented from competing and she was thus reinstated. "On August 5th, I had my ticket to [return home] to Russia at 2 o\'clock, and at 11 o\'clock, on the way to airport, they tell me I stay here [in Rio de Janeiro]. It was two weeks like this, in the morning we go, in the evening we don\'t." She went on to claim a silver medal in the individual time trial at the Games. (reuters.com, 11 Aug 2016; tass.com, 06 Aug 2016)SANCTIONIn March 2014 she tested positive for the banned substance octopamine. She did not compete for 18 months from June that year, despite maintaining her innocence. In December 2015 the anti-doping commission of the Russian Cycling Federation [RCF] cleared her of any wrongdoing, which caused the International Cycling Union [UCI] to appeal the ruling to the Court of Arbitration for Sport [CAS]. In February 2016 the RCF announced that Zabelinskaya had reached a settlement with the UCI [an 18-month ban that expired in September 2015] that allowed her to continue competing and aim for a spot at the 2016 Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro. (fvsr.ru, 13 Feb 2016; ria.ru, 13 Feb 2016)NATIONAL FIRSTHer silver medal in the individual time trial at the 2016 Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro meant she became the first cyclist from the Russian Federation to win three medals in road cycling at the Olympic Games. (SportsDeskOnline, 10 Aug 2016)BREAKIn 2007 she began a three-year hiatus from cycling before returning in 2010. "I was tired of the sport, took a rest and came back." (Athlete, 23 Apr 2016) '), ('Relatives', 'Her father Sergei Sukhoruchenkov won gold in road cycling at the 1980 Olympic Games in Moscow. (Athlete, 23 Apr 2016)'), ('Injuries', 'In April 2010 she was involved in an accident in Lido di Camaiore, Italy. She was hit by a car while cycling and taken to hospital where she was diagnosed with haematoma of the liver as a result of the collision. She was discharged from hospital a few days later and returned to light training.
